status: NEEDS_FIXES
strengths: [`src/rateLimiter.js:38-44` has clear factory-time validation for finite positive numeric config, `src/rateLimiter.js:56-68` keeps window pruning isolated and easy to reason about, `src/rateLimiter.js:71-75` adds bounded global cleanup for untouched keys, `src/rateLimiter.test.js:10-21` uses a deterministic injected clock, `src/rateLimiter.test.js:99-165` and `src/rateLimiter.test.js:263-309` cover the core sliding-window and boundary behavior well, verification run: `node --test src/` -> `# tests 19`, `# pass 19`, `# fail 0`]
critical_issues: none
important_issues: [`src/rateLimiter.js:39-44` accepts fractional `limit` values even though `limit` is a request count; `src/rateLimiter.js:81-89` then produces nonsensical API output such as `limit: 1.5` allowing two requests and returning `remaining: -0.5` on the second allowed request. Validate `Number.isInteger(limit)` or explicitly define rounding semantics and test them.]
minor_issues: [`src/rateLimiter.test.js:45-68` does not test `NaN` or `Infinity` despite the validation contract covering them, `src/index.js:1-14` is a pragmatic test-runner shim but would be misleading as a production package entry because it imports tests instead of exporting the limiter, `src/rateLimiter.js:60-62` and `src/rateLimiter.js:74` use simple array splicing and full key snapshots; fine for moderate limits/key counts, but a head-index queue and non-copying sweep would scale better.]
